{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e64864b9-5209-4677-9a72-7701e1ddd9d7","content":"In MSTest 3.x (which you're using), the recommended pattern is:\n\n- **Constructor** — accepts `TestContext` via injection; use for sync setup\n- **`[TestInitialize]`** — supports `async Task`; use for async setup\n- **`[TestCleanup]`** or `IAsyncDisposable` — for cleanup\n\nHere's the idiomatic setup:\n\n```csharp\n[TestClass]\npublic class MyTests : IAsyncDisposable\n{\n    private readonly TestContext _testContext;\n    private HttpClient _client;\n\n    public MyTests(TestContext testContext)\n    {\n        _testContext = testContext;\n        // Synchronous init (runs first)\n    }\n\n    [TestInitialize]\n    public async Task InitializeAsync()\n    {\n        // Async init (runs before each test, after constructor)\n        _client = new HttpClient();\n        await _client.GetAsync(\"https://example.com/health\");\n    }\n\n    [TestMethod]\n    public async Task MyTest()\n    {\n        _testContext.WriteLine(\"Running test...\");\n        // ...\n    }\n\n    [TestCleanup]\n    public async Task CleanupAsync()\n    {\n        // Async per-test cleanup\n    }\n\n    public async ValueTask DisposeAsync()\n    {\n        if (_client is not null)\n            _client.Dispose();\n    }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n- **Constructor injection** of `TestContext` is supported in MSTest v3+ — no need for the old `public TestContext TestContext { get; set; }` property pattern.\n- The **execution order** is: Constructor → `[TestInitialize]` → `[TestMethod]` → `[TestCleanup]` → `Dispose`/`DisposeAsync`.\n- `[TestInitialize]` and `[TestCleanup]` both support `async Task` return types.\n- Use `IAsyncDisposable` (or `IDisposable`) as an alternative to `[TestCleanup]` for resource cleanup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"0219c62b-50f7-43c5-bd68-0482036223e3","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is on MSTest 3.8.2 with .NET 9.0. Let me provide the modern recommended approach for MSTest test class initialization with constructor injection for TestContext and both sync/async initialization.\n\nIn modern MSTest (v3+), the recommended approach is:\n\n1. **Constructor injection for `TestContext`** — you can accept `TestContext` as a constructor parameter instead of using the property setter pattern.\n2. **`IAsyncInitialization`** — MSTest doesn't have a built-in `IAsyncInitialization` interface. For async initialization, you use `[TestInitialize]` with an async method.\n\n\n3. **Async methods** — Both `[TestInitialize]` and `[TestCleanup]` can be async (returning `Task`), and you can implement `IDisposable` or `IAsyncDisposable` for cleanup logic.\n\nI'm setting up a test class that demonstrates constructor injection of `TestContext`... Cleanup methods can also be async with `Task` return types, and both `IDisposable` and `IAsyncDisposable` patterns work for resource cleanup in MSTest 3.x.","outputTokens":1054,"requestId":"57D7:1D73CD:2E4281E:311D1B3:6A0494D3"},"id":"26b9f65d-874c-4cbe-8d54-aa6486cb6663","timestamp":"2026-05-13T15:12:40.610Z","parentId":"e6c3f895-2259-4689-a744-e816802537ab"}
